  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "When the Universe Had No Rest Mass — The Electroweak‑Symmetric Era",
    "description": "Teaching‑style explainer of the epoch when the Higgs vacuum expectation value is zero and all Standard Model particles are massless, with interactive calculations.",
    "keywords": ["cosmology","early universe","electroweak","Higgs","sphaleron","baryogenesis","radiation domination"],
    "author": {"@type": "Person", "name": "E‑Jay"}
  }
  </script>
</head>
<body>
  <a class="pill" href="#main" style="position:absolute;left:-1000px;top:-1000px">Skip to content</a>
  <div class="container" id="main">
    <header class="hero">
      <div>
        <h1>When the Universe Had <em>No Rest Mass</em><br/>The Electroweak‑Symmetric Era</h1>
        <p class="lede">A rigorous, teaching‑style tour of the early universe when the Higgs field had zero vacuum expectation value (\u27E8H\u27E9 = 0), so all Standard Model rest masses vanished. We clarify <span class="pill">rest mass vs thermal mass</span>, the status of forces and symmetries, thermodynamics and expansion, and common pitfalls.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="grid-2">
          <div>
            <div><span class="pill">Gauge group</span></div>
            <p class="eq">SU(3)<sub>c</sub> \u00D7 SU(2)<sub>L</sub> \u00D7 U(1)<sub>Y</sub> (unbroken)</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div><span class="pill">Equation of state</span></div>
            <p class="eq">radiation: p = \u03C1/3, a(t) \u221D t<sup>1/2</sup></p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div><span class="pill">Relativistic d.o.f.</span></div>
            <p class="eq">g* = 106.75 (Standard Model)</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div><span class="pill">Typical epoch</span></div>
            <p class="eq">T \u223C 150\u2013170 GeV \u2192 t \u223C 10<sup>\u221211</sup> s</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <nav class="toc">
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Contents</strong>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#massless">What \u201Cno mass\u201D really means</a></li>
          <li><a href="#forces">Forces & symmetries above electroweak breaking</a></li>
          <li><a href="#content">Particle content & degrees of freedom</a></li>
          <li><a href="#thermo">Thermodynamics & expansion</a></li>
          <li><a href="#higgs">Higgs sector at high temperature</a></li>
          <li><a href="#kinetics">Kinetics: collisions, screening, sphalerons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#numbers">Interactive snapshot</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pitfalls">Common pitfalls</a></li>
          <li><a href="#glossary">Glossary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">Check your understanding</a></li>
          <li><a href="#refs">Notes & further reading</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <section id="massless">
      <h2>1) What \u201Cno mass\u201D really means</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Rest mass vanishes, but medium effects do not</h3>
          <p>At temperatures T \u2265 \u223C 150\u2013170 GeV the Higgs vacuum expectation value is zero, so <strong>all Standard Model rest masses are zero</strong>: fermions have no Yukawa mass terms and the <span class="eq">W</span>/<span class="eq">Z</span> bosons have no Proca masses. However the hot plasma generates <strong>thermal (screening) masses</strong> of order <span class="eq">\u223C g\,T</span> for gauge and matter fields. These are <em>not</em> rest masses; they parametrize collective behavior (Debye screening, Landau damping) and disappear as the medium is removed.</p>
          <div class="callout"><h4>Definition</h4>
            <p><strong>Rest mass</strong>: invariant mass parameter in the vacuum Lagrangian.<br/>
               <strong>Thermal mass</strong>: momentum‑dependent self‑energy in a medium; sets screening scales, not a vacuum mass.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Radiation equation of state</h3>
          <p>All species are ultra‑relativistic, giving the radiation equation of state <span class="eq">p = \u03C1/3</span>. The energy density and entropy density are</p>
          <p class="eq">\u03C1 = (\u03C0<sup>2</sup>/30)\,g*\,T<sup>4</sup>,\quad s = (2\u03C0<sup>2</sup>/45)\,g*\,T<sup>3</sup>.</p>
          <p class="note">Here <span class="eq">g*</span> counts effective relativistic degrees of freedom in equilibrium.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="forces">
      <h2>2) Forces & symmetries above electroweak breaking</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul class="list-check">
          <li><strong>Gauge group unbroken:</strong> <span class="eq">SU(3)<sub>c</sub> \u00D7 SU(2)<sub>L</sub> \u00D7 U(1)<sub>Y</sub></span>.</li>
          <li><strong>No photon/Z mass eigenstates:</strong> the familiar photon and Z arise only after symmetry breaking. Above the transition, the plasma supports <em>gauge eigenmodes</em> (\u03B2=hypercharge \u2192 <span class="eq">B_\u03BC</span>, weak isospin \u2192 <span class="eq">W^a_\u03BC</span>).</li>
          <li><strong>Range of forces set by screening:</strong> without Proca masses, interactions would be long‑range in vacuum, but in the hot medium they are cut off at the Debye/magnetic screening lengths, both temperature‑dependent.</li>
          <li><strong>Electric charge still a generator:</strong> <span class="eq">Q = T_3 + Y/2</span> as a group relation holds above the transition; the <em>propagating</em> eigenstates in medium are not the broken‑phase photon/Z mixture.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="content">
      <h2>3) Particle content & degrees of freedom</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li>All quarks and leptons are effectively massless and in equilibrium (including top).</li>
          <li>QCD is <strong>deconfined</strong>: the plasma contains free (screened) quarks and gluons; no hadronic bound states.</li>
          <li>Counting only the Standard Model, the relativistic d.o.f. is <span class="eq">g* = 106.75</span>.</li>
          <li>Neutrinos are tightly coupled; decoupling occurs much later (\u223C MeV scale).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="thermo">
      <h2>4) Thermodynamics & expansion</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Radiation domination</h3>
          <p>In this era the Friedmann equation with radiation gives <span class="eq">a(t) \u221D t<sup>1/2</sup></span> and Hubble rate</p>
          <p class="eq">H(T) = \u221A{(8\u03C0 G/3)\,\u03C1(T)} \quad \text{with}\quad \u03C1(T) = (\u03C0<sup>2</sup>/30) g* T<sup>4</sup>.</p>
          <p>Equivalently, in natural units one often writes <span class="eq">H \u2248 1.66\, \sqrt{g*}\, T^2/M<sub>Pl</sub></span>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Orders of magnitude</h3>
          <p>At <span class="eq">T \u223C 160 GeV</span> with <span class="eq">g* = 106.75</span>, the cosmic time is <span class="eq">t \u2248 1/(2H) \u223C 10<sup>\u221211</sup> s</span> and the particle horizon is only millimeters. Energy densities are enormous, scaling as <span class="eq">T^4</span>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="higgs">
      <h2>5) Higgs sector at high temperature</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>The finite‑temperature effective potential restores electroweak symmetry so that <span class="eq">\u27E8H\u27E9 = 0</span>. The Higgs field acquires a <em>thermal mass</em> \u223C \u03BA T from plasma interactions, which stabilizes the symmetric minimum at high temperature. In the Standard Model with <span class="eq">m<sub>h</sub> \u2248 125 GeV</span> the subsequent cooling triggers an <strong>electroweak crossover</strong> (not a strong first‑order transition).</p>
        <div class="callout"><h4>Implication for baryogenesis</h4>
          <p>A smooth crossover provides too little out‑of‑equilibrium dynamics for successful electroweak baryogenesis within the SM. Many beyond‑SM models add scalars or new interactions to make the transition first‑order and to supply extra CP violation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="kinetics">
      <h2>6) Kinetics: collisions, screening, sphalerons</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Frequent collisions, short mean free paths</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Reaction rates scale as powers of gauge/Yukawa couplings and T; for typical couplings, <em>all</em> SM sectors remain in kinetic and chemical equilibrium.</li>
            <li><strong>Screening:</strong> electric Debye length scales like <span class="eq">\u03BB<sub>D</sub> \u223C 1/(gT)</span>; magnetic screening in non‑Abelian plasmas arises non‑perturbatively at <span class="eq">\u223C 1/(g<sup>2</sup>T)</span>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Sphalerons & charges</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Non‑perturbative <span class="eq">SU(2)<sub>L</sub></span> transitions (sphalerons) are <strong>unsuppressed</strong> in the symmetric phase and violate <span class="eq">B+L</span> while conserving <span class="eq">B\u2212L</span>.</li>
            <li>Any pre‑existing <span class="eq">B+L</span> is driven to zero; successful scenarios create a <span class="eq">B\u2212L</span> asymmetry earlier (e.g., high‑scale leptogenesis) or engineer dynamics at the transition.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="numbers">
      <h2>7) Interactive snapshot</h2>
      <div class="card panel">
        <div class="inputs">
          <div class="row">
            <label for="T"><strong>Temperature</strong> <span class="note">(GeV)</span></label>
            <input id="Tn" type="number" min="10" max="2000" step="1" value="160" />
          </div>
          <input id="T" type="range" min="10" max="2000" step="1" value="160" aria-label="Temperature slider in GeV" />

          <div class="row" style="margin-top:.6rem">
            <label for="gstar"><strong>g*</strong> <span class="note">(relativistic d.o.f.)</span></label>
            <input id="gstar" type="number" min="10" max="200" step="0.25" value="106.75" />
          </div>

          <div class="row" style="margin-top:.6rem">
            <label for="gauge"><strong>Gauge coupling g</strong> <span class="note">(for thermal scales)</span></label>
            <input id="gauge" type="number" min="0.05" max="2.0" step="0.01" value="0.65" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="outputs">
          <div class="kv"><div>Temperature</div><code id="Tk"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Energy density \u03C1 (SI)</div><code id="rhoSI"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Energy density \u03C1 (natural)</div><code id="rhoNat"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Hubble rate H</div><code id="H"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Cosmic time t \u2248 1/(2H)</div><code id="t"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Horizon scale c t</div><code id="horizon"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Horizon scale</div><code id="horizon_mm"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Thermal mass scale \u223C gT</div><code id="mthW"></code></div>
          <div class="kv"><div>Debye length \u03BB<sub>D</sub> \u223C \u0127c/(gk<sub>B</sub>T)</div><code id="deb"></code></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="note">The interactive panel computes with SI constants via <span class="eq">H^2 = (8\u03C0G/3)\,\rho/c^2</span> and <span class="eq">\rho = (\u03C0^2/30) g* (k_B T)^4/(\u0127^3 c^5)</span>. It assumes instantaneous radiation domination and ignores small changes of g* with T.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="pitfalls">
      <h2>8) Common pitfalls</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>\u201CMassless \u2192 no screening\u201D is false.</strong> Thermal masses and screening emerge from the medium even when vacuum masses vanish.</li>
          <li><strong>There is no photon above electroweak breaking.</strong> The massless U(1)<sub>EM</sub> emerges only after symmetry breaking; above it you have <span class="eq">B_\u03BC</span> and <span class="eq">W^3_\u03BC</span> gauge eigenfields in a plasma.</li>
          <li><strong>\u201CWeak force is always short‑range\u201D is misleading.</strong> Short range today is due to <span class="eq">m_W, m_Z</span>; in the symmetric phase, range is limited by <em>screening</em>, not a hard mass term.</li>
          <li><strong>Bound states/atoms don\u2019t exist here.</strong> QCD is deconfined; EM as we know it hasn\u2019t emerged; strong screening kills would‑be Coulombic binding.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="glossary">
      <h2>9) Glossary</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Rest mass</h3>
          <p>Invariant mass parameter in the Lagrangian. Generated by Yukawa couplings to the Higgs and by gauge symmetry breaking (for W/Z). Zero in this epoch.</p>
          <h3>Thermal mass</h3>
          <p>Medium‑induced self‑energy scale \u223C gT that sets screening; not a vacuum mass.</p>
          <h3>Debye length</h3>
          <p>Electric screening length in a plasma: interactions are exponentially screened beyond \u03BB<sub>D</sub>.</p>
          <h3>Sphaleron</h3>
          <p>Topological transition in electroweak theory that changes baryon and lepton numbers (violates B+L, conserves B\u2212L). Unsuppressed in the symmetric phase.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>g*</h3>
          <p>Effective number of relativistic degrees of freedom contributing to \u03C1 and s. In the SM with all species relativistic, g* = 106.75.</p>
          <h3>Radiation domination</h3>
          <p>Cosmic era with p = \u03C1/3 and scale factor a(t) \u221D t<sup>1/2</sup>.</p>
          <h3>Electroweak crossover</h3>
          <p>Smooth thermal transition near T \u223C 150\u2013170 GeV in the SM (for m<sub>h</sub> \u2248 125 GeV), not a first‑order phase transition.</p>
          <h3>Deconfined QCD</h3>
          <p>High‑T phase of QCD with quarks/gluons not bound into hadrons; occurs already at T \u223C 150 MeV, long before the electroweak epoch.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="faq">
      <h2>10) Check your understanding</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Why can the weak interaction be effectively short‑range even when m<sub>W</sub>, m<sub>Z</sub> = 0?</summary>
        <p>Because in a hot plasma, gauge fields acquire screening masses (electric) and non‑perturbative magnetic screening. These set a finite range \u223C \u03BB<sub>D</sub>, independent of any Proca mass term.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Does QED exist above the electroweak transition?</summary>
        <p>Not as a separate unbroken U(1)<sub>EM</sub> with a photon; the relevant gauge fields are hypercharge <span class="eq">B_\u03BC</span> and weak isospin <span class="eq">W^a_\u03BC</span>, whose medium eigenmodes are screened in the plasma.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What happens to any pre‑existing baryon asymmetry in this era?</summary>
        <p>Unsuppressed sphalerons violate B+L and drive it to zero in equilibrium. An asymmetry in B\u2212L can survive and later be partially converted into baryon number.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is electroweak baryogenesis hard in the SM?</summary>
        <p>The SM transition is a crossover (too smooth), and its CP violation is too small. A strong first‑order transition and additional CP violation (e.g., from new scalars) are typically required.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

